<h2 id="federal-incentives">Federal EV Tax Credits</h2>

<p>Regardless of which state you live in, federal tax incentives can significantly reduce the cost of purchasing or leasing an electric vehicle. The federal Clean Vehicle Credit, established under the Inflation Reduction Act, offers substantial savings:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>New EV Tax Credit:</strong> Up to $7,500 for qualifying new battery electric vehicles and plug-in hybrids. The vehicle must meet domestic manufacturing requirements and critical mineral sourcing thresholds.</li>
  <li><strong>Used EV Tax Credit:</strong> Up to $4,000 (or 30% of the sale price, whichever is less) for qualifying used electric vehicles purchased from a licensed dealer. The vehicle must be at least 2 model years old and priced at $25,000 or less.</li>
  <li><strong>Point-of-sale transfer:</strong> Starting in 2024, buyers can choose to transfer the credit to the dealer at the time of purchase, effectively reducing the purchase price immediately rather than waiting to claim the credit on their tax return.</li>
  <li><strong>Commercial clean vehicle credit:</strong> Businesses can claim up to $7,500 for qualifying light-duty EVs and up to $40,000 for heavier commercial EVs used for business purposes.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Federal Credit Income Limits</h3>

<p>The federal EV tax credit has income eligibility caps:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>New vehicles:</strong> Modified AGI must be below $300,000 for married filing jointly, $225,000 for head of household, or $150,000 for single filers.</li>
  <li><strong>Used vehicles:</strong> Modified AGI must be below $150,000 for married filing jointly, $112,500 for head of household, or $75,000 for single filers.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Federal Credit Vehicle Price Caps</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>SUVs, vans, and pickups:</strong> MSRP must not exceed $80,000</li>
  <li><strong>All other vehicles (sedans, hatchbacks, etc.):</strong> MSRP must not exceed $55,000</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="eligible-vehicles">Eligible Vehicles</h2>

<p>Not all electric vehicles qualify for the full federal tax credit. Eligibility depends on where the vehicle was assembled, where the battery components were manufactured, and where the critical minerals were sourced. The IRS maintains an updated list of qualifying vehicles at <a href="https://fueleconomy.gov/feg/tax2023.shtml">fueleconomy.gov</a>.</p>

<p>Popular qualifying vehicles typically include select models from:</p>

<ul>
