<h2 id="charging">Home Charging Considerations</h2>

<p>Beyond the vehicle purchase incentives, {{ state.name }} residents should factor in the cost and benefits of home charging:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Level 1 charging (120V):</strong> Uses a standard household outlet. Adds approximately 3-5 miles of range per hour. No installation cost, but slow charging makes it best suited for plug-in hybrids or low-mileage drivers.</li>
  <li><strong>Level 2 charging (240V):</strong> Requires a 240V outlet or hardwired installation. Adds 20-40 miles of range per hour. Installation typically costs $500-$2,000 depending on your home's electrical capacity.</li>
  <li><strong>Federal charging credit:</strong> The Alternative Fuel Vehicle Refueling Property Credit covers 30% of home charger installation costs, up to $1,000 for residential installations.</li>
  <li><strong>Utility incentives:</strong> Many electric utility companies in {{ state.name }} offer time-of-use rates that make overnight EV charging significantly cheaper. Some also offer rebates for charger installation.</li>
</ul>

